---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<PageLayout title="Sound Effects" slug="sketches/sound-effects">

<section class="demo-section" id="spectral-hedgehog">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>Spectral Hedgehog</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/01-spectral-hedgehog/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/01-spectral-hedgehog/index.html?embedded`} title="Spectral Hedgehog" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  The azimuthal angle around a sphere surface maps to a FFT bin. The radial distance at each point
  equals the base radius plus the FFT value at that angle, so the sphere grows spines wherever that
  frequency is loud — 128 independent spike bands visible simultaneously on one surface. Elevation is
  tapered so the poles stay smooth.
</p>
</div>
</section>

<section class="demo-section" id="bass-fold">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>Bass Fold</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/02-bass-fold/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/02-bass-fold/index.html?embedded`} title="Bass Fold" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  An iterated function system (Mandelbox-style: box fold + sphere inversion) where the number of fold
  iterations is driven by bass energy. At silence the geometry is a clean, symmetric blob. As bass
  rises the IFS folds accumulate, building fractal complexity — until at peak bass the surface is
  fully fractured and multi-scale.
</p>
</div>
</section>

<section class="demo-section" id="per-pixel-orbit">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>Per-Pixel Orbit</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/03-per-pixel-orbit/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/03-per-pixel-orbit/index.html?embedded`} title="Per-Pixel Orbit" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  Each screen pixel computes its own ray origin, displaced from the camera position by an amount
  proportional to the FFT value at the pixel's angular position on screen. The displacement is
  perpendicular to the viewing axis. The result is a prismatic multi-exposure effect — each
  neighbourhood of pixels sees the object from a slightly different vantage point, creating
  refractive bokeh driven by the audio spectrum.
</p>
</div>
</section>

<section class="demo-section" id="temporal-echo">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>Temporal Echo</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/04-temporal-echo/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/04-temporal-echo/index.html?embedded`} title="Temporal Echo" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  The same scene is rendered four times with <code>iTime</code> shifted by increasing offsets, each echo
  multiplied by a decreasing weight (1.0, 0.6, 0.35, 0.18). The temporal gap between echoes scales
  with overall amplitude — loud moments create wide motion smears, quiet passages snap the echoes
  tight. The shape becomes a time-integrated exposure of itself in motion.
</p>
</div>
</section>

<section class="demo-section" id="ray-warp">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>Ray Warp</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/05-ray-warp/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/05-ray-warp/index.html?embedded`} title="Ray Warp" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  Before ray marching begins, the ray direction is perturbed by a smooth vector field based on a
  radial function of screen position, scaled by the FFT value at the corresponding frequency band.
  This bends rays non-uniformly — some pixels point past the object, others curve back around. The
  effect resembles gravitational lensing through a medium whose refractive index is the audio spectrum.
</p>
</div>
</section>

<section class="demo-section" id="fft-columns">
<div class="demo-header">
<h2>FFT Columns</h2>
<a href={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/06-fft-columns/index.html`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">open full size ↗</a>
</div>
<div class="demo-embed">
<iframe src={`${base}/sketches/sound-effects/06-fft-columns/index.html?embedded`} title="FFT Columns" scrolling="no" allow="autoplay"></iframe>
</div>
<div class="prose">
<p>
  The screen is divided into vertical columns, each mapping to a FFT bin. The camera ray for that
  column tilts upward by an amount proportional to the bin's value. The scene is a horizontal plane
  of spheres, and each column independently aims at a different height of the same object, producing
  a 3D equaliser bar chart rendered in raymarched depth.
</p>
</div>
</section>

</PageLayout>
